post_text: Locker combinations, switching classrooms and time management are just some of the things Ms. Larson likes to prep her 5th graders with in the spring. With the school year being cut short last year, we were unable to introduce these now 6th graders to their new environment for the upcoming school year. All 6th graders are welcome to join us for a mini Open House on Thursday, August 27th at 6pm. Please enter through the high school office doors. Masks will be required and parents are asked to wait outside. Staff in attendance will be available to ask questions outside while socially distanced at the conclusion of the orientation. Can‚Äôt wait to see you!

post_text: The staff at Rapid River would like to recognize Brooke Lindbert for her dedication and hard work at Rapid River Schools. She makes volunteering here a full time job! Over the past several years, her vision & drive to continually improve our school has positively affected our students. She has been a leader of the elementary PTC group and incorporated multiple unique and successful fundraisers. She is a member of the RR School Board and takes that job very seriously. Recently, she stepped up to make the Class of 2020 graduation extra special by volunteering to take pictures of each graduate in her photography studio, putting together videos for each graduate, helping to organize the ‚Äúdrive in‚Äù graduation ceremony, coordinating the senior yard signs, uploading the senior slideshow to social media, and helping to advertise graduation/awards night on FB. Brooke‚Äôs passion and vision for Rapid River Schools helps to continually improve the district. Thank you, Brooke, for your endless energy and enthusiasm! You are appreciated beyond measure. üíúüíõ

Allison Gustafson was selected as the 2020 Outstanding Graduate for the Arts & Letters Division, with the award being sponsored by Bink‚Äôs Coca-Cola Bottling Company, the Bay Faculty Association, and the Bay College Foundation.

post_text: For families who planned on attending this next week, please note the Bonifas Art Center Youth in Art receptions have been cancelled.
shared_text:
Bonifas Arts Center
March 12 at 4:44 PM ¬∑

We have made the difficult decision to cancel the Youth In Art receptions on March 18th and 19th.

This decision does not come easy as we know the children and parents really look forward to coming to the reception but out of respect for our community and the request of our state government that gatherings larger than 100 people be postponed or cancelled, we are canceling the receptions.

We will be honoring the students with social media posts here and on our website and we encourage students and their parents to stop in on their free time to view all the artwork from the local students.

post_text: Mrs. Miller‚Äôs sophomore English class recently finished a unit on transcendentalism, an intellectual movement started in the mid 19th century that emphasized the dignity of the individual and advocated a simple, mindful life. After studying works by Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau and Margaret Fuller, the students proved their understanding of transcendentalism by designing and presenting their own society based on the basic precepts of it. Overall, they did a fantastic job! #sophomoreenglish #englishteacher #henrydavidthoreau #margaretfuller #ralphwaldoemerson

post_text:
Ms. Larson‚Äôs 5th grade class approached the School Board on Monday with their persuasive essays as to why they should be granted permission to attend Clear Lake in May. Some points made were: ‚ÄúWe would be able to stay off of our electronics‚Äù and ‚Äúwe will be doing chores and cleaning up after ourselves‚Äù.

This year had an extra special request- they would like to attend for 2 nights instead of the usual 1 overnight. With 15 parents signing up to chaperone, the Board approved their request, pending fundraising goals were met. The kids were thrilled!!

This is a motivated group of kids and parents who are very much looking forward to this exciting experience! Thank you, RR School Board for approving this trip!

PS- the kids are working at Jack's Restaurant Rapid River Michigan this weekend bussing tables & collecting donations to help fund their camp trip! Stop in and help them out. ü•∞

post_text:
TEACHER SPOTLIGHT: Mrs. Vicky Kirby

Vicky Kirby is a 3rd grade teacher. She received her associate‚Äôs degree from Bay College & her bachelor‚Äôs degree from NMU. She has 15 years of teaching & subbing experience, including the 5 years she has been at Rapid River. During her time here, she has taught kindergarten and third grade. Her favorite thing to do outside of school is spend time with her family, especially her three grandsons.She enjoys family time at her camp in Big Bay, MI where they go hiking to waterfalls, pick blueberries, swim, and have bonfires. She says, ‚ÄúThe best part about teaching is seeing the growth students make from the beginning of the year to the end when they are ready for the next grade. It really gives me a feeling of satisfaction and pride knowing I did my best and so did they!‚Äù

Vicky Kirby

post_text:
TEACHER SPOTLIGHT: Mrs. DeGrave

Mrs. Charlene DeGrave is a teacher at Rapid River Elementary School. She teaches Young 5s and Kindergarten students. She attended Rapid River Schools through 8th grade, then went on to graduate from Escanaba High School. She received an Associates degree from Bay College and received her teaching degree from NMU. Mrs. DeGrave is in her 38th year of teaching! She taught 3 years of Head Start, 2 years of Kindergarten at Hannahville Schools, and 33 years at Rapid River teaching Kindergarten. She is involved in the PTC and is a MEA Region 17 Representative. When she isn‚Äôt teaching, she enjoys family time, being with her sisters, reading, camping, and attending Broadway plays with her husband. Here is what she says about her goals for her Rapid River kindergarten classes, ‚ÄúI have always wanted to create a safe, warm, and pleasant atmosphere for my students and their families. I try to make the learning environment as enjoyable as possible because I genuinely believe the quote ‚ÄòTo Teach is to Touch a Life Forever!‚Äô ‚Äú

It's that time of year again! Our club is getting ready for our convention (DCON) in Green Bay where they learn leadership skills, network with other clubs and Kiwanis leaders, and about the power of volunteering. We have 27 members going this year and costs have gone up. We are welcoming donations to help with these expenses. If you feel you can help, please message the FB page or call Rapid River School at (906)474-6411 and leave contact information for someone to get in touch. Our members have donated a lot of their time and talents over the past year and are excited for this opportunity. Please help if you can!

post_text: Our 5th graders had a blast last Friday at Bay College!
shared_text:
Bay College Admissions
October 25, 2019 at 6:08 PM ¬∑

We closed out our 5th Grade Fridays by having the super-fun students from Big Bay De Noc School, Manistique Area Schools, Holy Name Catholic School, and Rapid River Public Schools join us! A favorite quote of the day was, "When I got here, I had no idea what I wanted to be! Now I know I want to be a physicist!" Then quietly just to me, "That's how you say it, right?" Ha!!! We're going to miss having 5th graders on campus! Bay College #bayistheway
text:
Our 5th graders had a blast last Friday at Bay College!

Bay College Admissions
October 25, 2019 at 6:08 PM ¬∑

We closed out our 5th Grade Fridays by having the super-fun students from Big Bay De Noc School, Manistique Area Schools, Holy Name Catholic School, and Rapid River Public Schools join us! A favorite quote of the day was, "When I got here, I had no idea what I wanted to be! Now I know I want to be a physicist!" Then quietly just to me, "That's how you say it, right?" Ha!!! We're going to miss having 5th graders on campus! Bay College #bayistheway

post_text:
Stacey and Becky Kuehl received the Golden Rocket award for taking the initiative to plant and maintain the flowers in the front beds at our main entrance. They have weeded, watered and spent their own time & money making sure the entrance to our school was beautiful. Gestures such as these have not only made our school look better, but they are a fantastic example as to what a difference our volunteers make. For this, we thank them and wanted them publicly recognized for their efforts.

‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢ Pictured from left to right: Becky Kuehl, Stacey Kuehl & Brooke Lindbert (RR School Board Secretary)

If you would like to nominate someone for the Golden Rocket Award, please submit this form: http://www.rapidriver.k12.mi.us/UserFiles/Servers/Server_346622/File/Volunteer%20Recognition.pdf

Do you shop on Amazon?
Did you know that every time you shop there, a % of your purchases can be donated to our school with no extra cost to you?

When you go to shop, simply go to smile.amazon.com and on the drop down menu, click "change" and then search for Rapid River School Foundation. Easy as that!

All the money donated to the RRSF is distributed based on grants requested from Rapid River School groups, teachers or whomever in the school has a need :)

post_text:
Lunch is on Us this summer!

When school lets out for summer, Meet Up and Eat Up kicks off! At Meet Up and Eat Up, we believe lunchtime should be healthy and fun! Lunches are available Monday through Thursday for all children 18 and younger. At no cost to your family, these midday meals are full of healthy fruits and veggies to help fuel kids all summer long.

Summer should be a time for kids to play, grow and learn - and Meet Up and Eat Up is the perfect place to do all three. No sign-up is required - join us for food and fun!

Call 211 or text Food to 877877 for a location near you!

Help us spread the word with your family, friends and co-workers.

shared_text:
RRNSports.com
April 19, 2019 at 1:16 AM ¬∑

The Rapid River High School softball team overwhelmed the Munising Mustangs in a doubleheader sweep on Thursday, winning both games by 15-0 scores. The first game went four innings, the nightcap went three innings. Natalie Belanger pitched two perfect games, not allowing a baserunner all afternoon. She had 19 strikeouts altogether. Kirsten Goodacre was 6-for-6 at the plate with four runs batted in, including a three-run homer. Cecilia Pilon had four hits in the doubleheader while Jaden Schwartz had a triple and three RBI in the nightcap. The Rockets host Negaunee on Monday.
